{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523728"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:58:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:58:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13918"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13918"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.37,0.21,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6537"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55826"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6537"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13918"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"},{"type":"tags","id":"1446"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44603"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55826"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with increasing left calf and foot pain. He has experienced left calf pain for the last eight months, especially when walking, but has noted that this has been progressively worsening. He has not sought any treatment prior to this presentation. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. He has been prescribed medications for both his hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. He smokes 20 cigarettes a day but does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. His left foot has obvious changes on inspection (Image) and is cold to touch. He is able to move his left toes and foot, but notes decreased sensation in his left foot.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient\u0027s current presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV heparin infusion","CT angiogram","Ankle-brachial pressure index","Digital subtraction angiography","Optimisation of his hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and smoking cessation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of acute-on-chronic limb ischaemia, likely due to progression of underlying peripheral artery disease. The history of claudication symptoms (calf pain when walking) for eight months, followed by a sudden worsening, along with the cold, discoloured foot and sensory changes, are consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. It provides detailed anatomical information about the arterial system, allowing for rapid assessment of the location and extent of arterial occlusion or stenosis. This information is crucial for planning appropriate revascularisation strategies, whether surgical or endovascular.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV heparin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is often used in the management of acute limb ischaemia if the cause is due to emboli to prevent clot propagation. However, it is not the most appropriate next step before imaging has been performed to confirm the diagnosis and guide further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnkle-brachial pressure index\u003C/strong\u003E (ABPI) is a useful non-invasive test for diagnosing and monitoring peripheral artery disease. However, in the acute setting with obvious signs of limb ischaemia, ABPI would not be the most useful next step to guide definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigital subtraction angiography\u003C/strong\u003E can provide detailed imaging of the arterial system and allows for simultaneous endovascular intervention. However, it is more invasive than CT angiography and is typically reserved for cases where intervention is planned based on initial CT findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptimisation of his hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and smoking cessation\u003C/strong\u003E are crucial for the long-term management of this patient\u0027s peripheral artery disease. However, these measures are not the immediate priority in the setting of acute limb ischaemia, where urgent imaging and revascularisation are needed to prevent limb loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter obtaining a CT angiogram, the next steps in management would likely include anticoagulation and urgent vascular surgery or interventional radiology consultation for revascularisation. Long-term management should focus on risk factor modification, including smoking cessation, blood pressure control, and lipid management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT angiography is the preferred initial imaging modality for suspected acute limb ischaemia, providing detailed anatomical information to guide management.","Acute-on-chronic limb ischaemia can present with a sudden worsening of symptoms in patients with pre-existing peripheral artery disease.","Smoking cessation, blood pressure control, and lipid management are crucial for long-term management of peripheral artery disease, but are not the immediate priority in acute limb ischaemia."],"references":["Leung L. Painful black toe. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2012;41:704-6. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/september/painful-black-toe"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41372"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13918"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20852"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20852"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nFAlMK7A57hIFG5djGVFteGHffUpj2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nFAlMK7A57hIFG5djGVFteGHffUpj2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":284}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41372"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:38:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:38:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6537"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55826"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel